      ###Vegetable intake on health study

    ##The following can be considered direct input into the Stata command box
. label variable id "Participant identification number"
. label variable sex "Sex"
. label variable age "Age"
. label variable genhlth "General health rating"
. label variable reggp "Has regular GP"
. label variable vegwk "Total vegetable serves per week"
. label define sex_lbl 1 "Male" 2 "Female"
. label define genhlth_lbl 1 "Excellent" 2 "Very good" 3 "Good" 4 "Fair" 5 "Poor"
. label define reggp_lbl 0 "No" 1 "Yes"
. label value sex sex_lbl
. label value genhlth genhlth_lbl
. label value reggp reggp_lbl
  ##Comment: The objective of the preface commands is to label binary and categorical data, which will allow the workflow to be easily understood as the analysis is being conducted. ‘sex’ and ‘reggp’ are binary variables and ‘genhlth’ is a categorical variable.
. summarize vegwk, detail
. histogram vegwk, width(2.5) start(0) frequency normal
. summarize reggp, detail
. codebook reggp
    ##Comment: The goal is to characterise the data of ‘vegwk’ and ‘reggp’. For ‘vegwk’, a histogram and summary statistics demonstrate that this is normally distributed data. ‘Reggp’ is binary data, therefore, observing the codebook output provides useful information into the distribution and spread of participant categories.
. histogram vegwk, by(, subtitle(Vegetable serves per week for those with or without regular GP)) by(reggp)
. regress vegwk i.reggp
    ##Comment: The first part will create a histogram that contrasts the regular GP group from the non-regular GP group and to describe it. The second line will perform a simple linear regression on vegetable serves in a week on regular GP status.
. regress vegwk i.sex age i.genhlth i.reggp
    ##Comment: sex, general health rating and having a regular GP require a dummy variable to be coded in the regression model, as they are either binary or categorical variables. For this example, we use “Male” as a reference point for sex, “Excellent” as a reference point for general health rating, and “No” as a reference point for having a regular GP.
Optional:
. pwcorr vegwk sex age genhlth reggp, sig
. regress vegwk i.sex age ib5.genhlth i.reggp
    ##Comment: The first line can be used as supplement to understand the Pearson’s correlation coefficients between the ‘vegwk’ and the explanatory variables. The second line can be used to have a health rating of 5 (Poor) as the reference point to avoid negative coefficients.

